**Abstract:** Major essay titled "Searle, Aquinas, and the Alternative" (dated October 11, 1994) critiquing John Searle's speech act theory. Argues that Searle's taxonomy of illocutionary acts shares problematic assumptions with Aquinas's view of language, particularly the priority of assertive (truth-stating) uses of language over practical uses. Proposes an alternative view where promising and commanding are more fundamental than asserting.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Important philosophical essay connecting Monasterio's critique of intellectualism to contemporary philosophy of language; shows how the practical/theoretical distinction applies to understanding language itself.

